<article xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" specific-use="sps-1.4" dtd-version="1.0" xml:lang="en" article-type="research-article"><front><journal-meta><journal-id journal-id-type="publisher-id">cint</journal-id><journal-title-group><journal-title>Contexto Internacional</journal-title><abbrev-journal-title abbrev-type="publisher">Contexto int.</abbrev-journal-title></journal-title-group><issn pub-type="ppub">0102-8529</issn><issn pub-type="epub">1982-0240</issn><publisher><publisher-name>Pontifícia Universidade Católica do Rio de Janeiro, Instituto de Relações Internacionais</publisher-name><publisher-loc>Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil</publisher-loc></publisher></journal-meta><article-meta><article-id pub-id-type="publisher-id" specific-use="scielo-v2">S0102-85292013000200009</article-id><article-id pub-id-type="publisher-id" specific-use="scielo-v1">S0102-8529(13)03500200009</article-id><article-categories><subj-group subj-group-type="heading"><subject>Articles</subject></subj-group></article-categories><title-group><article-title>BRICS: an explanation in critical geography</article-title></title-group><contrib-group><contrib contrib-type="author"><name><surname>Meena</surname><given-names>Krishnendra</given-names></name><xref ref-type="aff" rid="aff01"/></contrib></contrib-group><aff id="aff01"><institution content-type="orgname">Jawaharlal Nehru University</institution><institution content-type="orgdiv1">School of International Studies </institution><institution content-type="orgdiv2">Centre for International Politics, Organization and Disarmament (CIPOD)</institution><email>meena.krishnendra@gmail.com</email></aff><pub-date pub-type="epub-ppub"><month>12</month><year>2013</year></pub-date><volume>35</volume><issue>2</issue><fpage>565</fpage><lpage>593</lpage><history><date date-type="received"><day>25</day><month>09</month><year>2013</year></date><date date-type="accepted"><day>04</day><month>11</month><year>2013</year></date></history><permissions><license license-type="open-access" xlink:href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" xml:lang="en"><license-p>This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License.</license-p></license></permissions><abstract><p>BRICS, an abbreviation for Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa, a group of five influential and emerging economies successfully completed its fifth annual summit in Durban during March 26-27, 2013. A significantly unique feature of the group is its geographical spread as evident from the location of these five constituent states which are situated in four continents. The paper seeks to explain the phenomenon of the disparate group BRICS through literature in Critical Geography as it is understood that the recent phase of globalization has created spatial patterns which were hitherto not experienced and therefore not clearly recognized in the literature on International Relations and traditional geography. Such spatially variegated groupings like the BRICS could be analyzed and interpreted in Critical Geography and Critical Geopolitics literature through three important concepts: a) Space b) Geographical and Geopolitical Imaginations and c) Region. The paper seeks to explain BRICS through these conceptual tools.</p></abstract><kwd-group xml:lang="en" kwd-group-type="author-generated"><kwd>BRICS</kwd><kwd>Critical Geography</kwd><kwd>Geopolitical Imaginations</kwd></kwd-group><counts><fig-count count="0"/><table-count count="0"/><equation-count count="0"/><ref-count count="39"/><page-count count="29"/></counts></article-meta></front><back><ref-list><ref id="B1"><element-citation publication-type="journal"><article-title>The Territorial Trap: The Geographical Assumptions of International Relations Theory</article-title><source>Review of International Political Economy</source><date><year>1994</year></date><fpage>53</fpage><lpage>79</lpage><issue>n. 1</issue><volume>v.1</volume><person-group person-group-type="author"><n